 focuses on the cases of the ex-post HDIA, the Bangladesh study will not be discussed here. For research findings, please see Razzaque (2005). Expiry of the WTO ATC A reduction in trade revenue Human Development Concerns Job Losses for Garment Workers A reduction in Public Expenditures on Social Services A Decline in Real Wages Gender-diferentiated Impacts Lower price of garments Lower volume of exports Increased pricecompetition Increased competition A change in Trade Policy Transmitting Channels If not compensated by other tax revenues. Downward pressure on wages Factory closures, retrenchment - - Lack of nutritious balance, long working hours, shorter contract terms, increased stress and dissatisfaction at work and in life, deterioration in health; - De-empowerment in negotiating for higher wages, better working conditions, skill development; - Changes in time-use at home and bargaining power - Deterioration in family's economic and social well-beings, including garment workers\u2019 children and/or siblings\u2019 education, their health care and other needs. Cutting the expenditures on the necessities Seeking cost- savings activities by not meeting CSRs A decline in remittance Policy Implications Trade Policies and Industrial Policies; e.g., better trade facilitation, lower interest rates, better supply of utilities\u2026 People as the development agencies of Enhancing pro-poor trade competitiveness - Discouraged workers - De-empowerment - Possible engagement in economically and socially risky activities for survival Training for Human Social Policies Labour Policies Education, Development Pro-poor Budget to support these policies Case of assessing the impacts of the expiry of the WTO Agreement on Textiles and Clothing (ATC) Capability Unobsernable latent variable Y1* \u03b31 \u03b32 \u03b33 Y1 Y2 Y3 \u03b34 \u039b1 \u039b2 \u039b3 \u03a71 \u03a72 \u03a73 \u03a74 \u03b61 \u03b62 \u03b63 \u03b64 \u03b51 \u03b52 \u03b53 Observable variables Causes, Xs Observede va