e32f602063f3a3ddd3def54842d240153a8feade4dbec1ff"}}, "hash": "698fb3836fd48e08134bc5f6e7624ff911ce9fce7b4b5dfb7a4c4dc2ce2b3b5e", "text": "What were damages to the community and households? What were damages to people and their physical and mental health, property, livelihoods, community facilities and services, the environment? \uf0b7 Who in the community were affected? How were adults, elderly and children affected? What were physical, economic, political, cultural, and psychosocial effects on men, women, boys and girls, and the elderly? \uf0b7 What are other threats to the community? To women? To men? To boys? girls? To the elderly? \uf0b7 How do the community, families, men, women prepare for, respond to and recover from disasters and threats? \uf0b7 What are organized efforts and processes to deal with disasters? \uf0b7 Who assists the community and families? The trash slide at the Payatas dumpsite in Quezon City death tolls was 224 (plus missing), mostly women and children, as houses in Lupang Pangako (Promised Land) were buried in the morning of July 10, 2009 after heavy rains from 2 successive typhoons. Source: Office of Civil Defense, 2003 Integrating Gender into Community Based Disaster Risk Management Training Manual 13 Natural Hazard and Disaster Impact in the Philippines 1. Natural Hazard Exposure The Philippines is one of the countries in the world that is prone to natural hazards. It recorded a total of 373 disaster events triggered by natural hazards from 1905 to 2006 or about 4 incidents per year (OFDA/CRED, 2006). The country\u201fs exposure to disaster is largely due to its location and geographic landscape. Composed of 7,107 islands, it is one of the world\u201fs largest archipelagos. It has a long coastline which makes it vulnerable to sea-level rise from climatic conditions. The Philippines is located along the Pacific Ring of Fire, making it vulnerable to earthquake, tsunamis and volcanic hazards. It has 220 volcanoes, 22 of which are classified as active. It lies along the Western Pacific Basin, a generator of climatic conditions such as monsoons, thunderstorms, intertropical convergence zones, typhoons and El Ni\u00f1o. On the average, 20 tropical cyclones cross the Philippine area of responsibility annually. The damaging elements of tropical cyclones are high winds, storm surges and floods. 2. Impact of Disasters The impact of disasters in terms of lives lost and damage to property is staggering. Deaths from natural disasters in the 1990 decade and in 2000-2006 have increased compared with the 1980 decade levels. A significant number of deaths are caused by tropical cyclones. The National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) has estimated that an average of 500 people are killed each year due to tropical cyclones during the period 1970-2002. The high number of deaths in the 90s was mainly due to the 1990 earthquake that struck Luzon and the 1991 Mt. Pinatubo eruption wherein lives lost numbered about 2,000 and 6,200 respectively. The NDCC recorded a tot1al number of 36,019 deaths caused by natural disasters from 1980 to 2006 (Table 1). Table 1. Deaths from Natural Disasters in the Philippines: 1980-2006 Years 1980 - 1989 1990 - 1999 2000-2006 No. of Deaths 3,217 24,247 8,555 Source: NDCC The average cost of direct damage from natural disasters from 1970 to 2006 is estimated at PhP15 billion at year 2000 prices (Table 2.2). Direct damage covers damage to agricultural crops, public infrastructure and private homes. Damage is highest at about PhP70 billion in 1978 when 15 disasters struck the country. Other major disasters with high direct damage are the Luzon earthquake in 1990 (about PhP66 billion), the Mt. Pinatubo eruption in 1991 (about PhP33 billion) and the droughts in 1984 and 1987. As a result, the declines in gross domestic product (GDP) were estimated at: (a) 1.2 percent due to the 1990 Luzon earthquake; (b) 0.9 percent due to the Pinatubo eruption; and (c) 0.5 percent average due to typhoons every year. Integrating Gender into Community Based Disaster Risk Management Training Manual 14 Table 2. Estimated Damage of Disasters in Million Pesos at 2000 Prices Years 1970-1979 1980-1989 1990-1999 2000-2006 Cost of damage 119,076 140,570 223,303 61,911 Natural calamities strain the national budget.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9cd13543-1d78-4e00-81e1-aef4714eda0e": {"__data__": {"id_": "9cd13543-1d78-4e00-81e1-aef4714eda0e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/integrating-gender-community-based-disaster-risk-management", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Integrating Gender into Community-based Disaster Risk Management", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/integrating-gender-community-based-disaster-risk-management", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "13158890c50e304e34aeb79fd5a4308ec14d3b3fac91d2b6ee04a730d962c74c"}, "2": {"node_id": "29f70a49-5c65-4f0f-8d4d-f038730c8d48", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/integrating-gender-community-based-disaster-risk-management", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "698fb3836fd48e08134bc5f6e7624ff911ce9fce7b4b5dfb7a4c4dc2ce2b3b5e"}}, "hash": "7d75ffbed24b0e9ee32f602063f3a3ddd3def54842d240153a8feade4dbec1ff", "text": "Limited budgetary resources meant to finance basic services such as farm-to-market roads, school buildings, and