sp Women Men Women Men Women Men Women Men Women Men Integrating Gender into Community Based Disaster Risk Management Training Manual 55 Learning Objectives At the end of this session the participants are able to: 1. Link existing gender and power relations to the socio-economic political context of the community and society. 2. Describe the key steps in the CBDRM process. 3. Discuss considerations for gender-sensitive CBDRM. Key Points 1. Gender and power relations are contextualized within society\u2018s socio- economic political and historical development. 2. Gender equality in CBDRM addresses differing vulnerabilities of men and women and mobilizes their different resources, knowledge, skills and experiences for family and community safety and development. 3.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1557b7dd-9154-466f-996b-1acca7300d09": {"__data__": {"id_": "1557b7dd-9154-466f-996b-1acca7300d09", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/integrating-gender-community-based-disaster-risk-management", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Integrating Gender into Community-based Disaster Risk Management", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/integrating-gender-community-based-disaster-risk-management", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "42e98eecb466e2164f9dedb097de03a2d832efe4fbbb46c02f32e9cda9881be4"}, "2": {"node_id": "10342372-4f45-4e5e-8949-618495850140", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/pu